How to customise individual cards

# Introduction

![https://camo.githubusercontent.com/3c88f79fe41b92aceec41ee3774d0eac623cb80d/68747470733a2f2f6661726d382e737461746963666c69636b722e636f6d2f373833362f34353635303038333639355f663863366365323930665f6e2e6a7067](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

<a id="_Ref23832640"></a>Figure 1 \- Example default card

The example default card shown in Figure 1 is not very appealing\. This section illustrates all the different ways you can customise the appearance of individual cards, including

- Add an image;  
Replace the yellow section at the top of the card with an engaging image of your choice\.
- Change the background colour;  
If you’d prefer not to use an image, change the background of the top of the card from yellow to your choice of colour\.
- Add a date or date range;  
Specify a date or date range for the card, including the ability to specify the date by referring to a week number from the course site’s trimester\.
- Change the card label  
If your card is not – like Figure 1 \-  for a __Module__, then change that label or make it disappear\. 

# How to…Add a card image by URL

The first of two ways you can add a card image is by URL \(link\)\. This means that you have found an image that is already on the World\-Wide Web and its URL \(or link\)\. For example, the URL \- [https://djon\.es/images/GrandCanyon\.jpg](https://djon.es/images/GrandCanyon.jpg) \- is for a photo of the Grand Canyon\.

__Pre\-requisite: __To complete this step, you must have found the URL for the image you want to use\. [This page](https://support.google.com/websearch/answer/118238?co=GENIE.Platform%3DDesktop&hl=en) provides some instructions on how to find an image URL using the [Google Images](http://images.google.com)\.

1. Edit the content item for the card you are adding the image to\.
2. Paste the URL for your image after \(and on the same line\) as __Card Image:  
__Producing something like Figure 2
3. Save your work

When you view the page, the card should now be displaying the image from the URL you provided \(e\.g\. Figure 3\)\.

<a id="_Ref3297966"></a>Figure 2 \- Content item specifying a card image

![https://camo.githubusercontent.com/3f182026a522d295ac29b4f19b53fbacf3b6b564/68747470733a2f2f6661726d352e737461746963666c69636b722e636f6d2f343835332f33323639303638313836385f363864343033303063665f6e2e6a7067](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

__Troubleshooting: My card image doesn’t appear__

To double check that you have the correct URL for the image, open up a new browser window and paste the image URL into browser location\. As a result, your browser should open and display the image\.

If it doesn’t then your image URL is incorrect\.

# How to…Add a card image by uploading

If you have an image you’d like to use, but can’t find a URL for it you can upload the image to Blackboard and use it there\.

1. Make sure you have a copy of the image on your computer\.
2. Edit the content item for your card\.
3. Use [these instructions](https://suffolk.screenstepslive.com/s/1050/m/bb9/l/11549-how-do-i-embed-a-picture-or-image-as-part-of-an-item) to embed an image in the content item and ensure that the *Image Description* is __Card Image__\.  
It is suggested you embed the image at the bottom of the content item\.

Figure 4 shows a content item with the image uploaded\. This content item will produce a card exactly the same as Figure 3\.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref3298519"></a>Figure 4 \- Content item with image uploaded

# How to…make an image fit neatly in a card

![Card with a cut-off image](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref43296795"></a>Figure 5 \- Card with a cut\-off image

Not all \(or perhaps even many\) images will fit neatly into the image space on a card\. Some images will be too big\. Some too small\. Some will have [the wrong aspect ratio](https://www.shutterstock.com/blog/common-aspect-ratios-photo-image-sizes)\. For example, Figure 5 shows an image that has been cut off because it is too wide\.

There are three options you can use to make an image fit

1. cover;
2. contain; and,
3. manually resize the image\.

<br clear=”all” />

## Cover – the default

By default \(you don’t need to do anything for this to happen\) the card makes the image ["cover"](https://tailwindcss.com/docs/background-size/#cover) the available space\.  That is, it scales the width and height of the image to ensure there is no unfilled space\. 

If the image aspect ratio is wrong you end up with the problem shown in Figure 5\. Some part of the image extends beyond the available space and is invisible \(it is cropped\)\.

## Contain

As an alternative, you can tell the Card Interface to ["contain"](https://tailwindcss.com/docs/background-size/#contain) the image\. That is, scale the image height and width so that it fits entirely within the space without cropping or stretching\. For example, Figure 6\.

With some images, containing an image will result in an image that is too narrow to take up the full width of a card\. When this happens, the image will be centered as shown in Figure 7

![A screenshot of a cell phone Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,) <a id="_Ref43297288"></a>Figure 6 \- Card using "contain" to resize a large image

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref43297455"></a>Figure  \- Card with a centered, contained image

## Manually resize the image

If neither cover nor contain provide a suitable method, you can always manually resize or crop the image to produce an appropriate aspect ratio and size\.

To do this you will need to use an external tool such as PhotoShop, Paint3D, or one of the [free online services](https://www.google.com/search?q=resize+crop+image+how+to)\.

## Changing background colour

If you would like to change the background colour, add a valid [HTML colour name](https://www.w3schools.com/colors/colors_names.asp), a [colour hex code](https://www.color-hex.com/), or [rgb function](https://www.w3schools.com/cssref/func_rgb.asp)\. Figure 9__* *__provides three example cards with different colours specified using different means\. The first card \(from the left\) uses a HTML colour name – __lightsalmon__\. The second card uses a hex code \- __\#ff0000__\. The last card uses a rgb function – __rgb\(0,255,255\)__\.

There are many [HTML colour pickers](https://www.google.com/search?client=firefox-b-d&q=html+colour+picker) on the Web that can help you choose a colour\.

# How to…Add or change dates

To provide learners with guidance about when they should attend to a card, each card can have a specific date \(or date range\) associated with it\.   
Figure 10, provides three different examples of how card dates might be displayed\. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)<a id="_Ref3979994"></a>  
Figure 10 \- Card with a date

## Card Components for Dates

There are two components to adding a date to a card:

1. Card Date; and,  
Must be provided and specifies the date or date range for the card\.  The three cards in   
Figure 10 have the following Card Dates
	1. Week 1  
Specifies the Monday of Griffith University’s week 1 for the current trimester\.
	2. Feb 14  
A specific date\.
	3. Week 3\-5  
Specify a date range by separating the trimester week’s with a dash\. The same can be done with specific dates e\.g\. Mar 11\-Mar 25
2. Card Date Label\.  
Specifies the label displayed at the top of the date\. In   
Figure 10 there are three visible card date labels: *Commencing*, *Celebrating*, and *From*\. *Commencing* is the default\. 

See the following sections for more information on how to add dates to card and change the card date label\.

## Adding a specific date to a card

To add a date to a card similar to   
Figure 10, you add __Card Date: Mar 11__ as shown in Figure 11\. 

The format for the date is the month followed by the date\. The month should be specified as a three\-letter abbreviation \(e\.g\. Jan, Feb, Mar, Apr, May, Jun, Jul, Aug, Sep, Oct, Nov, Dec\)\.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref3980317"></a>Figure 11 \- Content item for card with date \(  
Figure 10\)

## Add the date using Griffith University trimester weeks

Rather than specify an explicit date, it is possible to use Griffith University trimester weeks \(as specified by [Griffith’s academic calendars](https://www.griffith.edu.au/academic-calendar-key-dates)\) to specify a date\. For example, Figure 12 shows a content item where the card date is specified using __Week 1__\. Meaning that the first day of Week 1 of the trimester \(or study period\) associated with the Blackboard course site will be used as the date\.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref3981045"></a>Figure 12 \- Content item using Griffith University trimester week for date

The content item in Figure 12 is converted into the card shown in Figure 13\. The Card Interface automatically translates *Week 1* into the date for the first day of Week 1 in the appropriate trimester \(Trimester 1, 2019\)\. The Card Interface also adds the number of the week to the display to help students and staff\.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref3981171"></a>Figure 13 \- Card example using Griffith University trimester date

## Adding a date range

It is possible to specify a date range by providing the start and end dates\. These data should be provided in either the 

- Specific date format – e\.g\. __Mar 11\-Mar 15  
__Both dates must be specific using both the abbreviated month and date\. Both dates separate by a dash\.
- Trimester week format – e\.g\. __Week 3\-5  
__Use the work __Week__ followed by two numbers \(from 1 through 12\) separated by a dash\.

## Change the card date label

The cards in both   
Figure 10 and Figure 13 use the same card label – __Commencing__\. This is the default card label\. To change the card label you add a line containing __Card Date Label: __followed by the new label you wish to use\. 

For example, Figure 14 shows a card with the card date label set to __Finish by__

# How to…use different card types and card labels

The Card Interface understands two types of card: information, and navigation\. The following table summarises the major differences between the two types of cards\.

__Card__

__Purpose__

__Blackboard Item__

__Affordances__

Information

Display small bit of information

Content item

Displays information, no link, Card label and Engage button NOT displayed\.

Navigation

Provide a link to and display a small bit of information about another resource

Content Folder, Web link, Discussion board, Assessment item or any other Blackboard item that produces a link to another resource

Displays card information and links to the other resource\. Card label displayed\. Engage button displayed\.

Figure 16 shows three cards\. The first card is an *Information* card\. The other two cards are *Navigation* cards\.

The *Information* card does not have an engage button as there is nothing to engage with by clicking\. It just provides a bit of descriptive text, which in this case talks about the purpose of this page\. 

The two *Navigation* cards have an engage button if the mouse is placed over these cards, then \(as shown by the second card Figure 16\) in the entire card will be surrounded by a blue border\. Clicking on a *Navigation *card will take the visitor to the link pointed to by the card\.

Both of the *Navigation *cards include a __Card Label__ – *Module* – and demonstrate the automated numbering of Navigation cards performed by the Card Interface\. i\.e\. in Figure 16 the first navigation card is *Module *__*1*__ and the second navigation card is *Module *__*2*__\. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref4395436"></a>Figure 16 \- Collection of two different card types

## Changing the card label

As shown in Figure 16, a navigation card can have a card label\. By default a navigation card has the label __Module__\. However, the card label can be changed or turned off\.

### Changing the card label

To change the card label, add a line to the description for the Blackboard item that includes

Card Label: newLabelName

For example, the Blackboard item in Figure 17 specifies a new card label – __Learning path__

![https://camo.githubusercontent.com/cf055e1105c73e98496d316b9a2887c1f0837b5a/68747470733a2f2f6661726d352e737461746963666c69636b722e636f6d2f343835352f33313632333631313034375f336338393431613961365f6e2e6a7067](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

<a id="_Ref4396169"></a>Figure 17 \- Blackboard item with different card label

Figure 18 shows the Card produced based on the item in Figure 17\.

![Card with new label](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

<a id="_Ref4396229"></a>Figure 18 \- Card with new label name

### Removing the Card label

If you don’t wish to give a navigation card a label, add to the Blackboard item a line containing Card Label: with an empty label\. For example, Figure 19 shows a Blackboard item with an empty Card Label\.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref4396428"></a>Figure 19 \- Navigation card with an empty label

Figure 20 shows the impact of the missing Card Label in the Blackboard item shown in Figure 19\. The Blackboard item in Figure 19 is used to produce the card in the middle of Figure 20\. 

The collection of three cards in Figure 20 are the same three cards \(with the change made in Figure 19\) shown in Figure 16\. The change made in Figure 19 creates two changes in Figure 20:

First, the middle card no longer has the __Module__ label, or any label at all\. 

Second, the last card now starts as Module __1__, rather than Module 2 in Figure 16\. Illustrating that a removing a label from a card results in it being removed from the automated sequencing of labels\.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref4396597"></a>Figure 20 \- Card collection with empty card label and renumbering

# How to…hide a card

Sometimes you don’t want a card to appear\. e\.g\. you don’t want students to access a quiz just yet\.

Since a card is just a different way to visualise a single Blackboard Content Item\. You hide the card by hiding the Blackboard Content Item\.

## Hiding a Blackboard Content Item

If you hover your mouse over an item's name an arrow icon should appear\. Click on it and you see the list of options \(e\.g\. Figure 21\)\.   

To make an item unavailable to students, click on the *Make Unavailable *option\.

Rather than manually make an item available or unavailable, you can use *Adaptive Release*\. One of the other course options shown above \(just under *Make Unavailable*\)\. Adaptive Release can be used to automate availability\. Make it available after a date, between two dates, available only to a particular group\.\.\.\.and much more

![Looking at the options for a Blackboard content item](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref43299068"></a>Figure  \- Options for a Blackboard content item

## What you will see in edit mode

With *edit mode *on you will still be able to see cards that you have hidden\. A card that has been hidden will show a message\. As shown in Figure 22\.

Cards with adaptive release applied will current NOT show any message\.

![A card showing the "hidden" message when it is unavailable.](data:image/png;base64,)

<a id="_Ref43299291"></a>Figure  \- Card for an unavailable item showing the "hidden" message

## What you and students will see when not in edit mode

With *edit mode *off you will see the cards closer to what students see\.

Cards that are marked unavailable will not be shown\.

Cards with adaptive release applied will not be shown, if you meet the adaptive release rules\. For example, if an item is limited only to people in a group\. You will only see the matching card if you are in the group\.
